    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\n1. Run your code and observe the outcome. \r\n    - *Hint: Make sure to type a number into the console to set the amount of paint you want.* \r\n2. *Discuss: Why does the `Painter` only paint one square regardless of how much paint you give it?*\r\n3. Update the code to use the variable holding the user input for the amount of paint as the argurment for the `set_paint()` method.\r\n    - *Hint: Where in your code is the user's input being stored?*\r\n",
    "start_sources": {
      "files": {
        "0": {
          "id": "0",
          "name": "main.py",
          "language": "py",
          "contents": "from neighborhood import Painter\n\n# Create new Painter object\naiden = Painter()\n\n# Define turn_right variable\ndef turn_right():\n  aiden.turn_left()\n  aiden.turn_left()\n  aiden.turn_left()\n\n# Declare variable for user input\nbuckets_paint = int(input(\"How much paint do you want? \"))\n\n# Set the amount of paint the Painter has\naiden.set_paint(1)\n\n# Run your code here\nwhile aiden.has_paint():\n  if aiden.can_move():\n    aiden.move()\n    aiden.paint(\"white\")\n  else:\n    turn_right()\n",
          "folderId": "0",
          "active": true,
          "open": true
        }
      },
      "folders": {
      }
    },
